                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d309">
                <head>309. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the United
                        Kingdom</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d309fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 747C.00/2–1259. Secret. Repeated to Athens, Ankara, Nicosia, and
                        Paris for <gloss target="#t_USRO1">USRO</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>London</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1959-02-12T13:00:00+00:00">February 12, 1959, 1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4196. I had brief opportunity this morning to ask <persName corresp="#p_LS1"
                        >Lloyd</persName> his reaction to Greek-Turkish Cyprus agreement. He said
                    development most <pb facs="0802" n="768" xml:id="pg_768"/> welcome and that he
                    felt solution of problem is “in the bag” unless “the rats get at it.” To prevent
                    latter he felt quick action essential. [<hi rend="italic">2 lines of source text
                        not declassified</hi>] Believe he also had in mind possible reaction of his
                    own right-wing back-benchers.</p>
                <p>Later Gaitskell, who was also present, expressed his gratification. <persName
                        corresp="#p_LS1">Lloyd</persName> said details of agreement will be made
                    available to us earliest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJH1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Whitney</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
